<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;536.5 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Command and organizational relationships. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) The Secretary of the Army has delegated authority to The Judge Advocate General (TJAG) to assign areas of responsibility
and designate functional responsibility for claims purposes. TJAG has delegated authority to the Commander, U.S.
Army Claims Service (USARCS), to carry out responsibilities assigned in &sect;536.7(b). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) USARCS, a field operating agency of the Office of TJAG, is the agency through which the Secretary of the Army and
TJAG discharge their responsibilities for the administrative settlement of claims worldwide. (See AR 10&hyph;72.)
The proper mailing address of USARCS is Commander, U.S. Army Claims Service, Office of The Judge Advocate General,
Fort George G. Meade, Maryland 20755&hyph;5360. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) Command claims services. (1) Command claims services exercise general supervisory authority over claims matters
arising within their assigned areas of operation. Command claims services will provide_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Effective control and supervision of the investigation of incidents occurring within the geographic area of
the command, occurring in other areas for which the command is assigned claims responsibility or occurring in the
course of the command's operations. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Services for the processing and settlement of claims for and against the United States. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The commander of a major overseas command or other commands that include areas outside the United States, its territories,
and possessions, and report directly to the Department of the Army (DA) may be designated by TJAG to establish, a command
claims service. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) A command claims service may be a separate organization with a designated commander or chief. If it is part of the
Office of the Staff Judge Advocate (SJA) of the command, the SJA will also be the chief of the command claims service.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d) The following may be designated as area claims offices: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) An office under the supervision of the senior judge advocate (JA) of each command or organization so designated
by the Commander, USARCS. The senior JA is the head of the area claims office. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940317-1-00053 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940317-1-00013 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4702 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(2) An office under the supervision of the senior JA of each command in the area of operations of a command claims service
so designated by the chief of that service after coordination with the Commander, USARCS (see &sect;536.7(c)(2)).
The senior JA in the office is the head of the area claims office. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The legal office of each engineer district within the United States and such other engineer commands or agencies
as designated by the Commander, USARCS with concurrence of the Chief of Engineers (COE) for all claims generated by
such districts, commands, or agencies. The district counsel or the attorney in charge of the legal office of the command
or agency is the head of the area claims office. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) Claims processing offices are normally small legal offices or subordinate elements of area claims offices, which
are designated by the Commander, USARCS; a command claims service; or an area claims office. These offices are established
for the investigation of all potential and actual claims arising within their jurisdiction, either on an area basis
or on a command or agency basis. A claims officer (see appendix B to this part) will not be a claims processing office;
his or her role is limited to claims investigation. There are four types of claims processing offices as follows (&sect;536.8(c)):

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Claims processing offices without approval authority. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Claims processing offices with approval authority. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Medical claims processing offices. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Special claims processing offices. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(f) The chief of a command claims service and the head of an area claims office or a claims processing office with approval
authority may delegate, in writing, any portion or all of his or her monetary approval authority to a subordinate JA
or claims attorney in his or her service or office. The authority to act upon appeals or requests for reconsideration,
to disapprove claims (including disapprovals based on substantial fraud), or to make final offers will not be delegated.
Copies of delegations within claims processing offices will be provided to the area claims office and, if so directed,
to command claims services. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
&sect;536.6 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Designation of claims attorneys. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a) The Commander, USARCS, the senior JA of a command having a command claims service or the Commander, USAREUR Claims
Service, the head of an area claims office, or the Chief Counsel, COE may designate a qualified attorney other than
a Judge Advocate as a claims attorney. The head of an area claims office may designate a claims attorney to act as a claims
processing office with approval authority. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) To be eligible as a claims attorney, an individual must be a civilian employee of the DA or DOD, in grade GS&hyph;11
or above; a member of the bar of a State, the District of Columbia, or a jurisdiction where U.S. Federal law applies;
and be performing primary duties as a legal adviser. These requirements can be waived by the Commander, USARCS, in
appropriate cases. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

