<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
In the adopting release to Rule 10b&hyph;10, the Commission explained that: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The rule does not attempt to set forth all possible categories of material information to be disclosed by broker-dealers
in connection with a particular transaction in securities. Rule 10b&hyph;10 only mandates the disclosure of information
which can generally be expected to be material. Of course, in particular circumstances, additional information
may be material and disclosure may be required. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Securities Exchange Release No. 13508, (May 5, 1977), 42 FR 25318, at 25320 n.28. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=3 -->
See also 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=28 g=1 f=1 -->
Securities Exchange Act Release No. 22397 (Sept. 11, 1985), 50 FR 37648, 37653 n.53 (indicating that disclosure of
a ``mark-up'' for national market system securities under Rule 10b&hyph;10 would not control traditional determinations
of, among other things, whether the mark-ups are excessive for purposes of the antifraud provisions of the federal
securities laws). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->
</FOOTNOTE>

